<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFF THE TICKER: DIRTY TRICKS AREN'T CRICKET, U.K. FINDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Britain's trade minister has personally intervened to withdraw a booklet 
sponsored by his department that recommended dirty business tricks such as 
going through competitors' trash. 
</P>
<P>
 Trade and Industry Secretary Michael Heseltine acted after reporters quizzed 
ministry officials on the contents of the booklet, a ministry spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
 She said the publication, Marketing Your Business, with the ministry's logo on 
the front, had been used in government-run business seminars since 1983.  
</P>
<P>
 Newspapers that saw copies of the booklet before it was banned reported it 
also advised entrepreneurs to befriend secretaries, or to pretend to be a 
newspaper researcher or a student writing a thesis, to gain access to rivals' 
secrets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
