<P>
 IBM to Cut 1,000 Jobs: The world's largest computer maker said that over the 
next few weeks it will cut 700 jobs from its microelectronics division, or 
about 5% of the division's work force. In the software solutions division, 300 
employees were notified that their positions will be eliminated.The reductions 
are part of a turnaround program that has slashed Big Blue's costs by $5.6 
billion since the end of 1992. IBM's losses totaled almost $15 billion in 1992 
and '93, largely because of plummeting revenue from mainframes. IBM aims to 
trim its work force in 1994 to 222,000, a reduction of about 35,000 employees. 
IBM shares rose 37.5 cents to $72.375 a share on the New York Stock Exchange on 
Friday. 
